@* HttpClient -> fetch (BENCH n°64, decision 147): the network enters the subset. The honesty argument
   mirrors decision 133's: Blazor WASM's HttpClient is implemented ON TOP of fetch -- the bridge exists
   because .NET must marshal across a boundary, and Filament IS the other side, so the bridge erases:

     await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("data/items.json")  ->  await __getJson('data/items.json')

   __getJson = fetch + throw on !ok (GetFromJsonAsync's EnsureSuccess semantics, catchable with #110's
   try/catch) + JSON.parse + a key normalizer faithful to System.Text.Json's Web defaults (camelCase,
   case-insensitive on the leading character). The type argument is GATED to JSON-faithful shapes:
   int/double/bool/string, records of those, List<T>/T[] of those -- long (BigInt), decimal ({m,s}),
   DateTime (ticks) and float (fround) members are REFUSED because a bare JSON number is not their
   representation. Relative URLs are faithful: BaseAddress is the host, fetch resolves against the
   document base.

   DOM contract: #list starts empty, #status "idle". #load fetches data/items.json (a static file BOTH
   shells serve -- deterministic) -> three <li> and "loaded 3", byte-identical vs Blazor. *@

@using System.Net.Http.Json
@inject HttpClient Http

<ul id="list">
    @foreach (Item it in items)
    {
        <li @key="it.Name">@it.Name: @it.Rank</li>
    }
</ul>

<p><span id="status">@status</span></p>

<button id="load" @onclick="Load">load</button>

@code {
    private List<Item> items = new List<Item>();
    private string status = "idle";

    private async Task Load()
    {
        var data = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("data/items.json");
        if (data != null)
        {
            items = data;
            status = "loaded " + items.Count;
        }
    }

    private record Item(string Name, int Rank);
}
